== PROTECTING BABY'S MICROBIOME

C-section babies miss the bacterial exposure of passing through the vaginal canal #citation[20]. This affects their gut microbiome—linked to immune development and long-term health.

=== What You Can Do

*Breastfeed if possible.* This is the most evidence-based intervention. Research shows cesarean babies receive more microbes from breast milk, compensating for what they missed #citation[14]. Exclusive breastfeeding for 6 months helps shift their microbiome toward the profile of vaginally born infants #citation[21].

*Vaginal seeding.* This involves swabbing baby's mouth, face, and body with gauze soaked in vaginal secretions immediately after birth. The goal: partially restore the bacterial exposure cesarean babies miss. One study showed better neurodevelopmental scores at 6 months #citation[6], and emerging research on the microbiome suggests this colonization pathway matters for immune development (see #link(<ch-microbiome>)[our Microbiome chapter] for the full picture).

Some families choose this; others don't. If you're considering it, screen yourself first—HIV, active genital herpes, Group B Strep, bacterial vaginosis, yeast infection, and sexually transmitted infections can all transfer to baby #citation[22]. If you're clear, here's the basic method: Before surgery, insert sterile gauze into the vagina for 1 hour. Remove it just before the cesarean begins and store in a sterile container. Immediately after birth, swab baby's mouth first, then face and body, within the first few minutes.

You may hear that vaginal seeding should only be done in clinical trials. That's one perspective. Another: this is your baby, your body, and your informed choice. If you understand the screening requirements and infection risks, you can make this decision yourself.

*Maximize skin-to-skin contact.* Skin bacteria transfer is another colonization pathway.

*Probiotics.* Some evidence supports probiotic supplementation in C-section babies, especially combined with breastfeeding #citation[23]. Families choose different approaches—some use infant probiotics from birth, others wait, and some don't use them at all.

