== VBAC: NEXT TIME

One cesarean doesn't mean you need cesareans forever.

=== Success Rates

60-80% of women who attempt VBAC (vaginal birth after cesarean) succeed #citation[1] #citation[12]. With favorable factors—prior vaginal birth, spontaneous labor, non-recurring reason for first cesarean—success can exceed 85% #citation[24].

=== The Risk That Gets Overemphasized

Uterine rupture risk during VBAC: 0.5-0.9% (about 1 in 100-200). This is real but comparable to other accepted birth risks. Most ruptures are detected early and managed successfully.

=== The Risks of Repeat Cesareans That Get Underemphasized

Each additional cesarean increases risk of:
- Placenta accreta (24% with previa + 1 prior C-section; 67% with 4+ prior C-sections) #citation[25]
- Adhesions and surgical complications
- Longer, more complex surgery
- Hysterectomy

=== Finding Support

Many hospitals ban or discourage VBAC despite ACOG recommending it be offered to most women with prior low transverse cesareans #citation[1]. If your provider won't support VBAC, find one who will. Ask: "What's your TOLAC success rate?"

